[1] Canada (New Brunswick, St John)
Date: Sat 1 Jun 2019
Source: The Star [abridged, edited]
https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2019/06/01/measles-outbreak-in-new-brunswick-continues-to-grow-medical-officer-says.html


The measles outbreak in New Brunswick, Canada has now spread to a 2nd high school; the 12 cases are all linked to the initial case. The province's chief medical officer, Dr Jennifer Russell, confirmed on Sat 1 Jun 2019 that the latest confirmed case is someone who either works or studies at Hampton High School, north east of Saint John.

As of Sat 1 Jun 2019, there were 12 confirmed cases of the highly contagious disease in the Saint John area, all of them linked to New Brunswick's 1st confirmed case, a person who travelled outside the province before showing up at Saint John Regional Hospital in late May 2019.

Russell said the other cases involve people exposed either at the emergency department at Saint John Regional or at Kennebecasis Valley High School. The latest case is linked to a previously confirmed case at Kennebecasis Valley High School, she said.

On Sat 1 Jun 2019, health officials said a special clinic would be set up to immunize those at Hampton High School who may have been exposed. "The fact that they're all directly linked is reassuring, in the sense that we know how everybody contracted measles," Russell said in an interview.

About 9000 doses of the vaccine have been distributed to deal with the outbreak, but many people in the province are having trouble getting a preventative shot. The New Brunswick Pharmacists' Association says local pharmacists have run out of the vaccine and likely won't get more until July 2019. Late last week, US health officials reported 971 measles cases so far this year [2019], the highest tally in 27 years.

[byline: Michael MacDonald]

