[3] Canada (Vancouver) and US (OR, WA)
Date: Thu 30 May 2019
Source: The Oregonian [abridged, edited]
https://www.oregonlive.com/health/2019/05/vancouver-area-measles-outbreak-spread-between-unvaccinated-children-at-home-in-church.html


At the end of 2018, a 10 year old girl arrived in Clark County from the Ukraine. She was taken to an urgent care clinic for a fever, cough and a skin rash that looked suspiciously like measles. Within 2 weeks, the girl and 12 more people tested positive for a strain of the measles virus that is currently running rampant in eastern Europe.

A report from the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention shows the Washington-Oregon outbreak was 1st incubated in homes and churches, where it spread quickly before dispersing into the Portland and Clark County communities. The report provides the 1st official insight into how the outbreak spread throughout the Vancouver area, other than an ever-growing list of potential infection locations released during the early winter. 30 of the 71 confirmed cases of measles were linked to each other. That transmission happened mostly at churches and in households where unvaccinated people passed the disease to each other.

Just over half of all the cases were spread within households, likely meaning that many of the cases were young relatives, such as siblings. A quarter of all cases were spread in churches. Only 5 churches were listed by Clark County Public Health as potential infection spots, which indicates that families with high infection rates might attend those churches and spread it to other unvaccinated people.

Clark County has one of the lowest vaccination rates in Washington, a state already lagging behind much of the country in immunizations. Since 2013, Clark County has been 10% to 14% behind the 88% vaccinated statewide average.

[byline: Molly Harbarger]

