[8] US: New measles cases break 25 year old record, health officials say 971 so far this year in US
Date: Thu 30 May 2019
Source: National Public Radio [abridged, edited]
https://www.npr.org/2019/05/30/728382757/new-u-s-measles-cases-breaks-25-year-old-record-health-officials-say?t=15593948


The number of new measles cases in the United States so far this year [2019] has hit 971, exceeding a record established 25 years ago that covered a whole year of new measles cases, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported on Thu 30 May 2019. The federal figures show that most of the new cases this year [2019] have been concentrated in New York City and Rockland County, NY, where the virus has been spreading mostly among unvaccinated children in Orthodox Jewish communities.

There have been 550 confirmed cases of measles in New York City since September 2018, according to the city's public health officials. Those caught unvaccinated in 4 Brooklyn ZIP codes can face fines up to USD 1000.

CDC officials warned that if the current rate of outbreaks continues, the virus may lose its status as being eliminated in the US, which public health experts have been worrying about since measles outbreaks starting occurring in recent years. "That loss would be a huge blow for the nation and erase the hard work done by all levels of public health," federal health officials said in a statement. Widespread vaccination efforts overseen by the CDC had virtually eliminated measles from the United States by 2000. But health officials say it has been reintroduced by people who have traveled to other countries.

Earlier this week, the CDC reported that the tally of new measles cases had reached 940, which was the highest since 1994, when 963 cases were reported from an entire year, officials said. The new numbers mean that the 1st 5 months of 2019 have officially surpassed the year-end total in 1994. Two years earlier, in 1992, the nation saw more than 2200 measles cases.

To be sure, the recent uptick in new measles cases is a far cry from the 1950s, when millions of people caught measles and hundreds died each year from the virus, CDC data show. Vaccinations against the highly contagious virus are widespread across the US, with some 94% of kindergartners having received vaccination coverage, according to CDC. In response to the recent resurgence, CDC says it is further strengthening state and local programs aimed at spreading the word that the safest and most effective way to protect against measles is to get vaccinated.

The World Health Organization reports that more than 82 500 measles cases across Europe were reported last year [2018], a significant surge from the previous year. Officials on Thu [30 May 2019] said vaccination is especially important when traveling to places currently dealing with measles outbreaks, including Israel, Brazil, Japan, the Philippines and some countries in Europe and Africa.

[byline: Bobby Allyn]

